          transliteration: "abhyuddharannatha dharāṁ daśanāgralagna-\nmustāṅkurāṅkita ivādhikapīvarātmā |\nuddhūtaghōrasalilājjaladhērudañca-\nnkrīḍāvarāhavapurīśvara pāhi rōgāt ||",
          translation: "Thus lifting the Earth — which clung to Your tusk-tip like a musta-grass sprout — Your mighty form rising from the ocean, shaking off the terrible waters, O Lord of playful Boar-form, O Ishvara, protect me from disease!",
          commentary: "The closing verse contains the signature Bhattathiri prayer. The Earth on the Boar's tusk is compared to a 'mustankura' — a tiny grass sprout stuck to a boar's tusk after rooting in the ground. This domesticated, familiar image applied to a cosmic event is poetic genius: the entire Earth is as insignificant as a grass-blade to the Lord. The compound 'krida-varaha-vapu' (one whose boar-form is mere play) reiterates divine effortlessness. The final plea 'Ishvara pahi rogat' (O Lord, protect from disease) connects Bhattathiri's personal suffering to the cosmic rescue — just as the Lord saved the Earth, may He save the poet.",
